<statement>
<p>A triangle has sides with lengths <m>\displaystyle{a}={6.00}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{b}={7.71}</m>, and <m>\displaystyle{c}={6.00}</m>. Calculate all of the angles of this triangle.</p>
<p>A=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{a}={6.00}</m>)</p>
<p>
  B=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{b}={7.71}</m>)</p>
<p>
  C=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{c}={6.00}</m>)</p>
<p>Round to two decimal places.</p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>50.02</li><li>79.96</li><li>34.35</li></ul></p><p>Because we have all three sides, we can use the law of cosines for the first angle.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{6}^{{2}}={7.71}^{{2}}+{6}^{{2}}-{2}{\left({7.71}\right)}{\left({6}\right)}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{36}={59.4441}+{36}-{92.52}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{59.4441}=-{92.52}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.6425}={\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{A}={50.021508186385}={50.02}</m>.</p>
<p>For a second angle, we can use the shorter law of sines.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{\sin{{\left({50.021508186385}\right)}}}}{{6.00}}=\frac{{\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}}{{7.71}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{0.31040601276209}={\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={\arcsin{{\left(-{0.31040601276209}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={79.95698362723}\approx{79.96}</m></p>
<p>The third angle we can calculate using the angle sum property.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{50.021508186385}+{79.95698362723}+{C}={180}^{\circ}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{C}={34.349361360673}\approx{34.35}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

